@node Readability scoring
@section Readability scoring

@findex eww-score-readability
The built-in function @code{eww-score-readability} determines which part of a
web page contains the main textual content for @code{eww-readable}.  It
excludes @code{script}, @code{head}, and @code{comment} tags from scoring, but does not
exclude @code{style} tags.  CSS text inside @samp{<style>} elements is therefore
counted as readable content, which can cause CSS-heavy nodes (such as
Wikipedia's @samp{div.navbox-styles}) to win the readability contest over the
actual article.  The result is an empty buffer because the selected node
contains only invisible CSS@.

This package uses @code{el-patch} to add @code{style} to the exclusion list in
@code{eww-score-readability}, giving @samp{<style>} elements a score of -2 (the
same penalty applied to @code{script} and @code{head}).  As an additional safety
net, @code{eww-extras-readable-autoview} detects when the readable render
produces an empty buffer or a result smaller than 2% of the HTML source
size, and falls back to displaying the full page
(@ref{Readability management}).

@node Readability node selection
@section Readability node selection

@findex eww-highest-readability
The built-in function @code{eww-highest-readability} selects the DOM node
with the highest readability score for @code{eww-readable}.  It replaces the
current best node with a deeper child whenever the child scores higher
and contains more than 100 words.  On pages where navigation-heavy
elements (navboxes, table of contents, categories) drag down the full
content node's aggregate score, a small subsection—such as the lead
paragraph—can win the readability contest over the full article.

This package uses @code{el-patch} to raise the minimum word threshold from a
fixed 100 to @code{max(100, 1/3 of the current best node's word count)}.
This ensures a child must contain a substantial fraction of the
parent's text to replace it, preventing narrow subsections from winning
over broader content areas.

